SIMPLE: materialism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Materialism
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>mat⟦eacute⟧rialisme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The doctrine of
materialists; materialistic views and tenets; called also
<altname>philosophical materialism</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The irregular fears of a future state had been supplanted by the
<qex>materialism</qex> of Epicurus.</q>
<rj><qau>Buckminster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The tendency to give undue importance to material
interests as contrasted with spiritual concerns; devotion to the
material nature and its wants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Material substances in the aggregate; matter.</def>
<mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>A. Chalmers.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>philosophical materialism</b></col> <cd>The theory that
matter and energy are the only objects existing within the universe, and
that mental and spiritual phenomena are explainable as functions of the
nervous system of people. Same as <er>materialism</er>{1}.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 902 --></p>

<p><ent>Materialist</ent>⟦br⟧
